Main members[edit]
The Danish royal family includes:

HM Queen Margrethe II of Denmark and HRH Prince Henrik of Denmark

TRH Crown Prince Frederik and Crown Princess Mary

HRH Prince Christian of Denmark
HRH Princess Isabella of Denmark
HRH Prince Vincent of Denmark
HRH Princess Josephine of Denmark


TRH Prince Joachim of Denmark and Princess Marie of Denmark

HH Prince Nikolai of Denmark
HH Prince Felix of Denmark
HH Prince Henrik of Denmark
HH Princess Athena of Denmark




HRH Princess Benedikte, Dowager Princess of Sayn-Wittenstein-Berleburg
HM Queen Anne-Marie of Greece
HH Princess Elisabeth of Denmark

Royal family of Greece[edit]
Main article: Greek royal family
Most of the members of the deposed royal family of Greece hold the title of Prince or Princess of Greece and Denmark with the qualification of His or Her Highness, pursuant to the Royal Cabinet Order of 1774 and as agnatic descendants of George I of Greece, who, as the son of the future King Christian IX of Denmark, was (and remained) a "Prince of Denmark" prior to his accession to the throne of Greece in 1863. Until 1953 his dynastic male-line descendants remained in Denmark's order succession. However, no Danish act has revoked usage of the princely title for these descendants, neither for those living in 1953, nor for those born subsequently or who have since married into the dynasty.
There are three members of the Greek royal family who are not known to bear the title of Prince/ss of Denmark with the qualification of His/Her Highness.[5][6][7]

Marina, consort of Prince Michael of Greece and Denmark

Princess Alexandra, Mrs. Mirzayantz
HRH Princess Olga, Duchess of Apulia



The following, consorts of royal monarchs today, were born with the titles of Prince/Princess of Greece and Denmark although they are not descended from King Constantine and Queen Anne-Marie:

HM Queen Sofia of Spain (King Constantine's sister and Queen Anne-Marie's sister-in-law)
HRH Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh (son of Prince and Princess Andrew of Greece and Denmark, grandson of King George I of Greece)

Royal family of Norway[edit]
Main article: Norwegian royal family
The royal family of Norway descends in the legitimate male line from Frederick VIII of Denmark, Queen Margrethe II's great-grandfather. Haakon VII of Norway, who was born Prince Carl of Denmark as Frederick VIII's younger son, was, like his uncle, George I of Greece, invited to reign over another nation. As with the Greek branch's descendants, members of the Norwegian line no longer have succession rights to the Danish crown, but unlike the Greek dynasts they discontinued use of Danish royal titles upon ascending their foreign throne in 1905.
Ducal family of Schleswig-Holstein[edit]
Main articles: House of Glücksburg § Duke of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Glücksburg, and Duke of Schleswig-Holstein-Sonderburg-Glücksburg
The Ducal Family of Schleswig-Holstein descends in the legitimate male line from Christian III of Denmark. As with the Greek branch's descendants, members of the Schleswig-Holstein line no longer have succession rights to the Danish crown, but unlike the Greek dynasts they discontinued use of Danish royal titles upon ascending their foreign throne in 1564.
Counts and Countesses of Rosenborg[edit]
Danish princes who marry without consent of the Danish monarch lose their dynastic rights, including royal title.[8] The ex-dynasts are then usually accorded the hereditary title "Count of Rosenborg". They, their wives, and their legitimate male-line descendants are:[9]

TE Count Ingolf of Rosenborg and Countess Sussie of Rosenborg (Prince Knud of Denmark's elder son and his wife)
TE Countess Josephine, Countess Camilla and Countess Feodora of Rosenborg (the daughters of Prince Knud of Denmark's late younger son, Count Christian of Rosenborg, and his late wife Countess Anne Dorte of Rosenborg)
TE Count Ulrik of Rosenborg and Countess Judi of Rosenborg (the son of Prince Harald of Denmark's younger son, Count Oluf of Rosenborg, and his wife)

HE Count Philip of Rosenborg (Count Ulrik's son)
HE Countess Katharina of Rosenborg (Count Ulrik's daughter)


HE Countess Charlotte of Rosenborg (the daughter of Prince Harald of Denmark's younger son, Count Oluf of Rosenborg)
TE Count Axel of Rosenborg and Countess Jutta of Rosenborg (the eldest son of Prince Axel of Denmark's younger son, Count Flemming Valdemar of Rosenborg, and his wife)

TE Count Carl Johan and Count Alexander of Rosenborg (Count Axel's sons)
TE Countess Julie and Countess Désirée of Rosenborg (Count Axel's daughters)


TE Count Birger of Rosenborg and Countess Lynne of Rosenborg (the second son of Prince Axel of Denmark's younger son, Count Flemming Valdemar of Rosenborg, and his wife)

HE Countess Benedikte of Rosenborg (Count Birger's daughter)


TE Count Carl Johan of Rosenborg and Countess Lisa Jeanne of Rosenborg (the third son of Prince Axel of Denmark's younger son, Count Flemming Valdemar of Rosenborg, and his wife)

TE Countess Caroline and Countess Josefine of Rosenborg (Count Carl Johan's daughters)


HE Countess Désirée of Rosenborg (the daughter of Prince Axel of Denmark's younger son, Count Flemming Valdemar of Rosenborg, and his wife)
HE Countess Karin of Rosenborg (widow of Count Christian of Rosenborg, the son of Prince Valdemar of Denmark's third son, Count Erik of Rosenborg)

HE Count Valdemar of Rosenborg (Count Christian's son)

HE Count Nicolai of Rosenborg (Count Valdemar's son)
HE Countess Marie of Rosenborg (Count Valdemar's daughter)


HE Countess Marina of Rosenborg (Count Christian's daughter)



